      "time": 1777209915942,
      "link": "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7444752687247634432?commentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Acomment%3A%28activity%3A7444752687247634432%2C7454158659271581697%29&dashCommentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afsd_comment%3A%287454158659271581697%2Curn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7444752687247634432%29",
      "text": "If it's not done in a \"clean room\" setup, it will most likely not hold in court. Some emulators were able to get over copyright claims because they could demonstrate they implemented everything from scratch without using anything more than the observed behavior of the system as a black box. Once you have the original code, those claims are hard to prove.\nIt could be enough to deter the usual copyright claims on GitHub, but this most likely won't hold in any court.",
