      "link": "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7444752687247634432?commentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Acomment%3A%28activity%3A7444752687247634432%2C7454087879481483264%29&dashCommentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afsd_comment%3A%287454087879481483264%2Curn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7444752687247634432%29",
      "text": "A missing .npmignore entry shipping 512,000 lines of unobfuscated TypeScript to the public npm registry is the kind of infosec story that will be featured in engineering onboarding decks for years. What makes it fascinating isnt the leak itself but what the code revealed: deliberate anti-detection systems built specifically to hide internal codenames. The gap between whats on the marketing page and what actually runs in prod is always wider than anyone expects..",
