    {
      "time": 1776094470325,
      "link": "https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7444752687247634432?commentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Acomment%3A%28activity%3A7444752687247634432%2C7449480141258371072%29&dashCommentUrn=urn%3Ali%3Afsd_comment%3A%287449480141258371072%2Curn%3Ali%3Aactivity%3A7444752687247634432%29",
      "text": "The intellectual property angle here is going to define the next decade of software law. When AI can translate proprietary code from one language to another in hours, traditional trade secret protection gets murky fast. It is not just Anthropic’s problem — any company building on top of AI-generated work is sitting on uncertain legal ground. This case is going to set a precedent that every enterprise AI team needs to watch closely. The organizations that start looping in legal now, before deploying significant AI-generated code to production, will be in a much stronger position when the dust settles.",
